About the problem: This problem involves application of properties of logarithms to simplify the difference of 2 logarithms and, equating sides, determine the unknown argument on the right-hand-side.


Full simplification and symbolic equality is enforced for answer checking.
Delete or comment out the <hint> to remove the Worked Example.

*************************************************************--> 
<problem><title/>
<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="a" from="1" to="3" exclude="$b"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="b" from="1" to="4"/>
  <select name="c">1 2</select>
  <math name="sol">4^($a) / (2^($b) 5^($c))</math>
  <math name="solSimp" simplify>4^($a) / (2^($b) 5^($c))</math>
  <math name="exprLHS" format="latex" simplify="numberspreserveorder">$a \log_b 4 - $b \log_b 2 - $c \log_b 5</math>
  <math name="exprRHS" format="latex">\log_b n</math>
  <!--maths for incorrect answers-->
</setup>


<!--testing-->
