<!--*********************************************
            Hint
**********************************************-->
<hint name="helpSection"><title>Worked Example</title>

  
<p>Here is a similar worked example:</p> 
<example>
<p><em>If <m>2\log_b 6 - 3\log_b 3 = \log_b n</m>, find <m>n</m>.</em></p> 
  
<p><em><alert>Solution.</alert></em></p>
<ul>
  <li>We apply the property of logarithms that
    <me>\log_b x^n = n\log_b x</me>
    and begin simplifying the left-hand side as follows:
    <md>
      <mrow>2\log_b 6 - 3\log_b 3 \amp= \log_b 6^2 - \log_b 3^3</mrow>
    </md></li>
  <li>Next, we combine the two terms on the left-hand side into a single term by applying the property of logarithms that
    <me>\log_b \frac{x}{y} = \log_b x - \log_b y.</me>
    This will simplify the expression to a single term as follows:
    <md>
      <mrow>\log_b 6^2 - \log_b 3^3 \amp= \log_b \bigg(\frac{6^2}{3^3}\bigg)</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp= \log_b \bigg(\frac{36}{27}\bigg)</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp= \log_b \bigg(\frac{4}{3}\bigg)</mrow>
    </md></li>
  <li>We can now compare our simplified expression to the right-hand side and equate corresponding terms to determine <m>n</m>,
    <md>
      <mrow>\log_b \bigg(\frac{4}{3}\bigg) \amp= \log_b n</mrow>
      <mrow>\frac{4}{3} \amp= n</mrow>
    </md></li>
</ul>
</example>




  
</hint>
  

<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->
<solution>
<ul>
  <li>Simplify the left-hand side,
    <md>
      <mrow>$exprLHS \amp=  \log_b 4^{$a} - \log_b 2^{$b} - \log_b 5^{$c}</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp=\log_b \bigg(\frac{4^{$a}}{2^{$b} \cdot 5^{$c}}\bigg)</mrow>
      <mrow>\amp=\log_b \bigg($solSimp\bigg)</mrow>
    </md></li>
  <li>Compare simplified expression to the right-hand side and equate corresponding terms,
    <md>
      <mrow>\log_b \bigg($solSimp\bigg)\amp= $exprRHS</mrow>
      <mrow>$solSimp\amp= n.</mrow>
    </md></li>
</ul>
    
</solution>
</problem>





